Problem 2

Question 1

Data Set 1: People over the age of 16 and who do not live in communal residences.

Data Set 2: Crimes recorded by the police.

Question 2

Data Set 1: The sampling strategy is stratified sampling.

Data Set 2: There is no sampling strategy as the police use their discretion when creating records and definitions of crime.

Question 3

Data Set 1: 38,000 people over the age of 16 who live in private residences in England and Wales.

Data Set 2: All administrative records of crime in the UK

Question 4

The target population of the study is people in the UK and Wales.

Question 5

Considering the reliability of each data set both are considered reliable for the first data set the vast size of the study and for the second data set the UK police employ the results of databases that take from all reported crimes. In terms of the validity, both appear to be valid, however with both data sets there may be issues with the self reporting and the under-reporting of certain crimes. With both data sets the study population are generalizable to the target population with those in England and Wales and those apart of the reported crimes in the UK through the records of the police.

The notation Hmisc:: directly calls this function from the Hmisc package. describe() is a common function name, and sometimes this is needed to indicate to R which function from which package you want to use. The pipe feature |> sends the results of the first line directly into the function on the 2nd line and is a convenient way to chain functions together.
